{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17618614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17618614"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:23:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16508"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16508","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16508"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.32,0,0.28,0.32,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65530"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16508"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50969"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"},{"type":"tags","id":"10343"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21819"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21826"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/65530"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinocerebellar tracts are major ascending pathways in the spinal cord that carry proprioceptive information from muscle spindles and Golgi tendon organs.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary projection target of the spinocerebellar tracts?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contralateral cerebellum","Ipsilateral somatomotor cortex","Ipsilateral cerebellum","Contralateral somatosensory cortex","Ipsilateral somatosensory cortex"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe spinocerebellar tracts project to the \u003Cstrong\u003Eipsilateral cerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E. This includes both the dorsal and ventral spinocerebellar tracts, which carry unconscious proprioceptive information from muscle spindles and Golgi tendon organs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral cerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E - Unlike many other pathways, the spinocerebellar tracts do not cross to the opposite side\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral somatomotor cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - The motor cortex receives input from other pathways, not the spinocerebellar tracts\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContralateral somatosensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - Conscious proprioception travels via the dorsal column-medial lemniscal pathway to the somatosensory cortex\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIpsilateral somatosensory cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - The somatosensory cortex receives input from other pathways, not the spinocerebellar tracts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum uses this proprioceptive information to help coordinate movements and maintain balance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The spinocerebellar tracts carry unconscious proprioceptive information from muscle spindles and tendon organs to the ipsilateral cerebellum.","The dorsal and ventral spinocerebellar tracts both terminate in the ipsilateral cerebellum, unlike many other sensory pathways which decussate.","The cerebellum uses proprioceptive information to coordinate movement and maintain balance."],"references":["Shrestha SS, Bannatyne BA, Jankowska E, Hammar I, Nilsson E, Maxwell DJ. Excitatory inputs to four types of spinocerebellar tract neurons in the cat and the rat thoraco-lumbar spinal cord. J Physiol. 2012 Apr 1;590(7):1737-55. doi: 10.1113/jphysiol.2011.226852. Epub 2012 Feb 27. PMID: 22371473; PMCID: PMC3413493.","Stecina K, Fedirchuk B, Hultborn H. Information to cerebellum on spinal motor networks mediated by the dorsal spinocerebellar tract. J Physiol. 2013 Nov 15;591(22):5433-43. doi: 10.1113/jphysiol.2012.249110. Epub 2013 Apr 22. PMID: 23613538; PMCID: PMC3853486.","Pop IV, Espinosa F, Blevins CJ, Okafor PC, Ogujiofor OW, Goyal M, Mona B, Landy MA, Dean KM, Gurumurthy CB, Lai HC. Structure of Long-Range Direct and Indirect Spinocerebellar Pathways as Well as Local Spinal Circuits Mediating Proprioception. J Neurosci. 2022 Jan 26;42(4):581-600. doi: 10.1523/JNEUROSCI.2157-20.2021. Epub 2021 Dec 2. PMID: 34857649; PMCID: PMC8805613.","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024).\u00a0Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022).\u00a0The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50969"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16508"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50969"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-26T15:14:56+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-26T23:20:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"65530"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},